    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1890-06-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1890-06-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="354"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d354">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Swift</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1890-06-12">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 12, 1890</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 81.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have your No. 120 of the 20th ultimo, stating
                    that you had communicated a copy of instruction No. 59 of the 18th of March
                    last, on the subject of the taxes which had been required by the Japanese
                    Government in respect of the sale of the American product “Scott’s Emulsion” to
                    the foreign office, but that no reply had been received.</p>
                <p>There is no occasion to renew representations unless the Japanese Government
                    should continue to tax the article and without submitting a reply to the views
                    of the Department. In that case, which is not anticipated, you will be justified
                    in pressing the protest further.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">James G. Blaine.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
